# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: traffic-shaping
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] In a Frame Relay network, **committed information rate** (**CIR**) is the bandwidth for a virtual circuit guaranteed by an internet service provider to work under normal conditions.
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] **Committed data rate** (**CDR**) is the payload portion of the CIR.
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] At any given time, the available bandwidth *should not* fall below this committed figure.
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] The bandwidth is usually expressed in kilobits per second (kbit/s).
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] Above the CIR, an allowance of burstable bandwidth is often given, whose value can be expressed in terms of an additional rate, known as the excess information rate (EIR), or as its absolute value, peak information rate (PIR).
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] The provider guarantees that the connection will always support the CIR rate, and sometimes the EIR rate provided that there is adequate bandwidth.
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] The PIR, i.e. the CIR plus EIR, is either equal to or less than the speed of the access port into the network.
[src:traffic-shaping/committed-information-rate] Frame Relay carriers define and package CIRs differently, and CIRs are adjusted with experience.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The **leaky bucket** is an algorithm based on an analogy of how a bucket with a constant leak will overflow if either the average rate at which water is poured in exceeds the rate at which the bucket leaks or if more water than the capacity of the bucket is poured in all at once.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] It can be used to determine whether some sequence of discrete events conforms to defined limits on their average and peak rates or frequencies, e.g. to limit the actions associated with these events to these rates or delay them until they do conform to the rates.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] It may also be used to check conformance or limit to an average rate alone, i.e. remove any variation from the average.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] It is used in packet-switched computer networks and telecommunications networks in both the traffic policing, traffic shaping and scheduling of data transmissions, in the form of packets, to defined limits on bandwidth and burstiness (a measure of the variations in the traffic flow).
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The generic cell rate algorithm, or an equivalent, may also be used to shape transmissions by a network interface card onto an ATM network.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] At least some implementations of the leaky bucket are a mirror image of the token bucket algorithm and will, given equivalent parameters, determine exactly the same sequence of events to conform or not conform to the same limits.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Two different methods of applying this leaky bucket analogy are described in the literature.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] These give what appear to be two different algorithms, both of which are referred to as the leaky bucket algorithm and generally without reference to the other method.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This has resulted in confusion about what the leaky bucket algorithm is and what its properties are.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In one version, the bucket is a counter or variable separate from the flow of traffic or schedule of events.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This counter is used only to check that the traffic or events conform to the limits: The counter is incremented as each packet arrives at the point where the check is being made or an event occurs, which is equivalent to the way water is added intermittently to the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The counter is also decremented at a fixed rate, equivalent to the way the water leaks out of the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] As a result, the value in the counter represents the level of the water in the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If the counter remains below a specified limit value when a packet arrives or an event occurs, i.e., the bucket does not overflow, that indicates its conformance to the bandwidth and burstiness limits or the average and peak rate event limits.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This version is referred to here as *the leaky bucket as a meter*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In the second version, the bucket is a queue in the flow of traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This queue is used to directly control that flow: Packets are entered into the queue as they arrive, equivalent to the water being added to the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] These packets are then removed from the queue (first come, first served), usually at a fixed rate, e.g., for onward transmission, equivalent to water leaking from the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This configuration imposes conformance rather than checking it, and where the output is serviced at a fixed rate (and where the packets are all the same length), the resulting traffic stream is necessarily devoid of burstiness or jitter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] So in this version, the traffic itself is the analogue of the water passing through the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This version is referred to here as *leaky bucket as a queue*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Thus, given equivalent parameters, the two algorithms will see the same traffic as conforming or nonconforming.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket as a queue can be seen as a special case of the leaky bucket as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Turner is credited with the original description of the leaky bucket algorithm and describes it as follows: "A counter associated with each user transmitting on a connection is incremented whenever the user sends a packet and is decremented periodically.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If the counter exceeds a threshold upon being incremented, the network discards the packet.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The user specifies the rate at which the counter is decremented (this determines the average bandwidth) and the value of the threshold (a measure of burstiness)".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The bucket (analogous to the counter) is, in this case, used as a meter to test the conformance of packets, rather than as a queue to directly control them.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Another description of what is essentially the same meter version of the algorithm, the generic cell rate algorithm, is given by the ITU-T in recommendation I.371 and in the ATM Forum's UNI specification.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If at a cell arrival the content of the bucket is less than or equal to the limit value *τ*, then the cell is conforming; otherwise, the cell is non-conforming.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The capacity of the bucket (the upper bound of the counter) is (*T* + *τ*)".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Spohn provide a commentary on the description given by the ITU-T/ATM Forum.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In this, they state, "In the leaky bucket analogy, the [ATM] cells do not actually flow through the bucket; only the check for conforming admission does".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, uncommonly in the descriptions in the literature, McDysan and Spohn also refer to the leaky bucket algorithm as a queue, going on, "Note that one implementation of traffic shaping is to actually have the cells flow through the bucket".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In describing the operation of the ITU-T's version of the algorithm, McDysan and Spohn invoke a "notion commonly employed in queueing theory of a fictional *gremlin*".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The difference between the descriptions given by Turner and the ITU-T/ATM Forum is that Turner's is specific to traffic policing, whereas the ITU-T/ATM Forum description is applicable to both traffic policing and traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Also, Turner does not state that the contents of the counter should only be affected by conforming packets, and should only be incremented when this would not cause it to exceed a limit, i.e.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Turner does not explicitly state that the bucket's capacity or counter's maximum value is finite.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A description of the concept of operation of the leaky bucket algorithm as a meter that can be used in either traffic policing or traffic shaping may be described as a fixed capacity bucket, associated with each virtual connection or user.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If the bucket is empty, it stops leaking.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] For a packet to conform, it has to be possible to add a specific amount of water to the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The specific amount added by a conforming packet can be the same for all packets or can be proportional to the length of the packet.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If this amount of water would cause the bucket to overflow, then the packet does not conform, and the water in the bucket is left unchanged.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket as a meter can be used in either traffic shaping or traffic policing.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In traffic policing, cells that do not conform to these limits (nonconforming cells) may be dropped or may be reduced in priority for downstream traffic management functions to drop if there is congestion.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In traffic shaping, cells are delayed until they conform.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Traffic policing and traffic shaping are commonly used in UPC and NPC to protect the network against excess or excessively bursty traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] (See bandwidth management and congestion avoidance.) Traffic shaping is commonly used in the network interfaces in hosts to prevent transmissions from exceeding the bandwidth or jitter limits and being discarded by traffic management functions in the network.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket algorithm as a meter can also be used in a leaky bucket counter to measure the rate of random (stochastic) processes.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A Leaky bucket counter can be used to indicate, by its overflowing when the average or peak rate of events increases above some acceptable background level.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] For example, such a leaky bucket counter can be used to detect when there is a sudden burst of correctable memory errors or when there has been a gradual, but significant, increase in the average rate, which may indicate an impending correction failure.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The use of the leaky bucket algorithm in a leaky bucket counter is similar to that in traffic management, in that it is used as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Essentially, the events replace the packets in the description, with each event causing a quantity of water to be added to the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If the bucket would overflow, as a result of the event, then the event should trigger the action associated with an out-of-limits event.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, other implementations may not increment the counter while it is overflowed, allowing it to correctly determine whether the following events conform or not.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In the case of the leaky bucket algorithm as a meter, the limits on the traffic can be bandwidth and the burstiness of the output.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The bandwidth limit and burstiness limit for the connection may be specified in a traffic contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A bandwidth limit may be specified as a packet rate, a bit rate, or as an emission interval between the packets.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A limit on burstiness may be specified as a delay variation tolerance, or as a maximum burst size (MBS).
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Multiple sets of contract parameters can be applied concurrently to a connection using multiple instances of the leaky bucket algorithm, each of which may take a bandwidth and a burstiness limit: see Generic cell rate algorithm § Dual Leaky Bucket Controller.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The rate at which the bucket leaks will determine the bandwidth limit, which is referred to as the average rate by Turner and the inverse of which is referred to as the emission interval by the ITU-T.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] It is easiest to explain what this interval is where packets have a fixed length.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, the first part of this description assumes this, and the implications of variable packet lengths are considered separately.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Consider a bucket that is exactly filled to the top by preceding traffic, i.e. when the maximum permitted burstiness has already occurred, i.e., the maximum number of packets or cells have just arrived in the minimum amount of time for them to still conform to the bandwidth and jitter limits.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The minimum interval before the next packet can conform is then the time it takes for the bucket to leak exactly the amount of water delivered by a packet, and if a packet is tested and conforms at that time, this will exactly fill the bucket once more.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Thus, once the bucket is filled, the maximum rate that packets can conform is with this interval between each packet.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Turner refers to this rate as the average, implying that its inverse is the average interval.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] There is, however, some ambiguity in what the average rate and interval are.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Since packets can arrive at any lower rate, this is an upper bound, rather than a fixed value, so it could at best be called the maximum for the average rate.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Also, during the time the maximum burstiness occurs, packets can arrive at smaller intervals and thus at a higher rate than this.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] So, for any period less than infinity, the actual average rate can be (but is not necessarily) greater than this and the average interval can be (but is not necessarily) less than the emission interval.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, because of this ambiguity, the term emission interval is used hereafter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, it is still true that the minimum value that the long-term average interval can take tends to be the emission interval.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, it is not possible to specify a specific emission interval for variable-length packets, and the bandwidth limit has to be specified explicitly, in bits or bytes per second.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] It is easiest to explain delay variation tolerance for the case where packets have a fixed length.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The ITU-T defines a limit value, *τ*, that is less than the capacity of the bucket by *T* (the amount by which the bucket contents is incremented for each conforming cell), so that the capacity of the bucket is *T* + *τ*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This limit value specifies how much earlier a packet can arrive than it would normally be expected if the packets were arriving with exactly the emission interval between them.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Imagine the following situation: A bucket leaks at 1 unit of water per second, so the limit value, *τ*, and the amount of water added by a packet, *T*, are effectively in units of seconds.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This bucket starts off empty, so when a packet arrives at the bucket, it does not quite fill the bucket by adding its water *T*, and the bucket is now *τ* below its capacity.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] So when the next packet arrives, the bucket only has to have drained by *T* – *τ* for this to conform.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] So the interval between these two packets can be as much as *τ* less than *T*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This extends to multiple packets in a sequence: Imagine the following: The bucket again starts off empty, so the first packet to arrive clearly conforms.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The bucket then becomes exactly full after a number of conforming packets, *N*, have arrived in the minimum possible time for them to conform.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] For the last (the *N*th) packet to conform, the bucket must have leaked enough of the water from the preceding *N* – 1 packets ((*N* – 1) × *T* seconds' worth) for it to be exactly at the limit value *τ* at this time.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, the water leaked is (*N* – 1) × *T* – *τ*, which, because the leak is one unit per second, took exactly (*N* – 1) × *T* – *τ* seconds to leak.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Thus, the shortest time in which all *N* packets can arrive and conform is (*N* – 1) × *T* – *τ* seconds, which is exactly *τ* less than the time it would have taken if the packets had been arriving at exactly the emission interval.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, packets can only arrive with intervals less than *T* when the bucket is not filled by the previous packet.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If it is filled, then the bucket must have drained by the full amount *T* before the next packet conforms.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] So once this bucket space has been used up by packets arriving at less than *T*, subsequent frames must arrive at intervals no less than *T*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] They may, however, arrive at greater intervals, when the bucket will not be filled by them.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Since the bucket stops leaking when it is empty, there is always a limit (*τ*) to how much tolerance can be accrued by these intervals greater than *T*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Since the limit value *τ* defines how much earlier a packet can arrive than would be expected, it is the limit on the difference between the maximum and minimum delays from the source to the point where the conformance test is being made (assuming the packets are generated with no jitter).
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, the use of the term cell delay variation tolerance (CDVt) for this parameter in ATM.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] As an example, a possible source of delay variation is where a number of streams of packets are multiplexed together at the output of a switch.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Assuming that the sum of the bandwidths of these connections is less than the capacity of the output, all of the packets that arrive can be transmitted eventually.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, if their arrivals are independent, e.g., because they arrive at different inputs of the switch, then several may arrive at or nearly at the same time.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Since the output can only transmit one packet at a time, the others must be queued in a buffer until it is their turn to be transmitted.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This buffer then introduces an additional delay between a packet arriving at an input and being transmitted by the output, and this delay varies, depending on how many other packets are already queued in the buffer.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A similar situation can occur at the output of a host (in the network interface controller) when multiple packets have the same or similar release times, and this delay can usually be modelled as a delay in a virtual output buffer.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] For variable-length packets, where the amount of water added by a given packet is proportional to its length, *τ* can not be seen as a limit on how full the bucket can be when a packet arrives, as this varies depending on the packet size.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, the time it takes to drain from this level to empty is still how much earlier a packet can arrive than is expected when packets are transmitted at the bandwidth limit.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Thus, it is still the maximum variation in transfer delay to the point where the conformance test is being applied that can be tolerated, and thus the tolerance on maximum delay variation.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The limit value or delay variation tolerance also controls how many packets can arrive in a burst, determined by the excess depth of the bucket over the capacity required for a single packet.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, MBS is also a measure of burstiness or jitter, and it is possible to specify the burstiness as an MBS and derive the limit value *τ* from this or to specify it as a jitter or delay variation tolerance or limit value, and derive the MBS from this.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A burst or clump of packets can arrive at a higher rate than determined by the emission interval *T*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This may be the line rate of the physical layer connection when the packets in the burst will arrive back-to-back.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, as in ATM, the tolerance may be applied to a lower rate, in that case, the Sustainable Cell Rate (SCR), and the burst of packets (cells) can arrive at a higher rate, but less than the line rate of the physical layer, in that case, the Peak Cell Rate (PCR).
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This bursting at the PCR puts a significantly higher load on shared resources, e.g., switch output buffers, than does transmission at the SCR, and is thus more likely to result in buffer overflows and network congestion.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, it puts a lesser load on these resources than would transmitting at the SCR with a limit value, *τSCR*, that allows MBS cells to be transmitted and arrive back-to-back at the line rate.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If the limit value is large enough, then several packets can arrive in a burst and still conform: if the bucket starts from empty, the first packet to arrive will add *T*, but if, by the time the next packet arrives, the contents is below *τ*, this will also conform.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Similarly, if *τ* is equal to or greater than (*T* – *δ*) × 2, then 3 packets can arrive in a burst, etc.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] In the case of ATM, where technically MBS only relates to the SCR tolerance, in the above equation the time it takes each packet to arrive, *δ*, is the emission interval for cells at the PCR *TPCR*, and the emission interval, *T*, is the emission interval for the SCR *TSCR*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Where MBS is to be the number of cells required to transport a segmented packet, the limit value in the above, *τ*, should be that for the SCR *τSCR*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, at the UNI or an NNI, where cells at the PCR will have been subjected to delay variation, it should be the limit value for the SCR plus that for the PCR *τSCR* + *τPCR*.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] For variable-length packets, the maximum burst size will depend on the lengths of the packets in the burst, and there is no single value for the maximum burst size.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, it is possible to specify the total burst length in bytes, from the byte rate of the input stream, the equivalent byte rate of the leak, and the bucket depth.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket algorithm is sometimes contrasted with the token bucket algorithm.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Both are effectively the same, as these are the same basic algorithm described differently.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket as a queue is essentially a way of describing a simple FIFO buffer or queue that is serviced at a fixed rate to remove burstiness or jitter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A description of it is given by Andrew S.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Tanenbaum, in (an older version of) his book *Computer Networks* as "The leaky bucket consists of a finite queue.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] When a packet arrives, if there is room in the queue, it is appended to the queue; otherwise, it is discarded.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] At every clock tick, one packet is transmitted (unless the queue is empty)".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] An implementation of the leaky bucket as a queue is therefore always a form of traffic shaping function.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] As can be seen, this implementation is restricted in that the packets are only ever transmitted at a fixed rate.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The tunable parameter for this algorithm is the bandwidth of its output.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The bandwidth limit for the connection may be specified in a traffic contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] A bandwidth limit may be specified as a packet or frame rate, a byte or bit rate, or as an emission interval between the packets.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Limiting variable-length packets using the leaky bucket algorithm as a queue is significantly more complicated than it is for fixed-length packets.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Tanenbaum gives a description of a "byte-counting" leaky bucket for variable-length packets as follows: "At each tick, a counter is initialized to n.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] If the first packet on the queue has fewer bytes than the current value of the counter, it is transmitted, and the counter is decremented by that number of bytes.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Additional packets may also be sent, as long as the counter is high enough.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] When the counter drops below the length of the next packet on the queue, transmission stops until the next tick, at which time the residual byte count is reset [to n] and the flow can continue".
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] As with the version for fixed-length packets, this implementation has a strong effect on the phase of transmissions, resulting in variable end-to-end delays, and unsuitability for real-time traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket as a queue can only be used in shaping traffic to a specified bandwidth with no jitter in the output.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] It may be used within the network, e.g. as part of bandwidth management, but is more appropriate to traffic shaping in the network interfaces of hosts.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket algorithm is used in Nginx's *ngx_http_limit_req_module* module for limiting the number of concurrent requests originating from a single IP address.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Analysis of the two versions of the leaky bucket algorithm shows that the version as a queue is a special case of the version as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Imagine a traffic shaping function for fixed-length packets that is implemented using a fixed-length queue, forming a delay element, which is serviced using a leaky bucket as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Imagine also that the bucket in this meter has a depth equal to the amount added by a packet, i.e., has a limit value, *τ*, of zero.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, the conformance test is only performed at intervals of the emission interval, when the packet at the head of the queue is transmitted and its water is added.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This water then leaks away during the next emission interval (or is removed just prior to performing the next conformance test), allowing the next packet to conform then or at some subsequent emission interval.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The service function can also be viewed in terms of a token bucket with the same depth, where enough tokens for one packet are added (if the bucket is not full) at the emission intervals.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This implementation will then receive packets with a bursty arrival pattern (limited by the queue depth) and transmit them on at intervals that are always exact (integral) multiples of the emission interval.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] The leaky bucket as a queue for variable packet lengths can also be described as equivalent to a special case of the leaky bucket as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, as the leaky bucket as a meter and token bucket are equivalent, the leaky bucket as a queue for variable packet lengths is also a special case of a traffic shaping function using a leaky bucket (or token bucket) as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] There is an interesting consequence of seeing the leaky bucket as a queue for variable packet lengths as a specific implementation of the token bucket or leaky bucket as a meter in traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] This is that the bucket of the meter has a depth, *n*, and, as is always the case with the token bucket, this depth determines the burstiness of the output traffic (perhaps in relation to the average or minimum number of tokens required by the packets).
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] Hence, it is possible to quantify the burstiness of the output of this *byte counting* leaky bucket as a meter, unless all packets are of the maximum length, when it becomes pointless.
[src:traffic-shaping/leaky-bucket] However, this ability to define a burstiness for the output is in direct contradiction to the statement that the leaky bucket (as a queue) necessarily gives an output with a rigid rate, no matter how bursty the input.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] In computer networking, **network traffic control** is the process of managing, controlling or reducing the network traffic, particularly Internet bandwidth, e.g. by the network scheduler.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] It is used by network administrators, to reduce congestion, latency and packet loss.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] In order to use these tools effectively, it is necessary to measure the network traffic to determine the causes of network congestion and attack those problems specifically.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] Network traffic control is an important subject in datacenters as it is necessary for efficient use of datacenter network bandwidth and for maintaining service level agreements.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] Traffic shaping is the retiming (delaying) of packets (or frames) until they meet specified bandwidth and or burstiness limits.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] Since such delays involve queues that are nearly always finite and, once full, excess traffic is nearly always dropped (discarded), traffic shaping nearly always implies traffic policing as well.
[src:traffic-shaping/network-traffic-control] Traffic policing is the dropping (discarding) or reduction in priority (demoting) of packets (or frames) that exceed some specified bandwidth and or burstiness limit.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The **token bucket** is an algorithm used in packet-switched and telecommunications networks.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] It can be used to check that data transmissions, in the form of packets, conform to defined limits on bandwidth and burstiness (a measure of the unevenness or variations in the traffic flow).
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] It can also be used as a scheduling algorithm to determine the timing of transmissions that will comply with the limits set for the bandwidth and burstiness: see network scheduler.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The token bucket algorithm is based on an analogy of a fixed capacity bucket into which tokens, normally representing a unit of bytes or a single packet of predetermined size, are added at a fixed rate.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] When a packet is to be checked for conformance to the defined limits, the bucket is inspected to see if it contains sufficient tokens at that time.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] If so, the appropriate number of tokens, e.g. equivalent to the length of the packet in bytes, are removed ("cashed in"), and the packet is passed, e.g., for transmission.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The packet does not conform if there are insufficient tokens in the bucket, and the contents of the bucket are not changed.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] A conforming flow can thus contain traffic with an average rate up to the rate at which tokens are added to the bucket, and have a burstiness determined by the depth of the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Implementers of this algorithm on platforms lacking the clock resolution necessary to add a single token to the bucket every $1/r$ seconds may want to consider an alternative formulation.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Given the ability to update the token bucket every S milliseconds, the number of tokens to add every S milliseconds = $(r*S)/1000$ .
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Over the long run the output of conformant packets is limited by the token rate, r .
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Let M be the maximum possible transmission rate in bytes/second.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Then $T_{\text{max}}={\begin{cases}b/(M-r)&{\text{ if }}r<M\\\infty &{\text{ otherwise }}\end{cases}}$ is the maximum burst time, that is the time for which the rate M is fully utilized.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The token bucket can be used in either traffic shaping or traffic policing.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] In traffic policing, nonconforming packets may be discarded (dropped) or may be reduced in priority (for downstream traffic management functions to drop if there is congestion).
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] In traffic shaping, packets are delayed until they conform.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Traffic policing and traffic shaping are commonly used to protect the network against excess or excessively bursty traffic, see bandwidth management and congestion avoidance.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Traffic shaping is commonly used in the network interfaces in hosts to prevent transmissions being discarded by traffic management functions in the network.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The token bucket algorithm is also used in controlling database IO flow.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] In it, limitation applies to neither IOPS nor the bandwidth but rather to a linear combination of both.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] By defining tokens to be the normalized sum of IO request weight and its length, the algorithm makes sure that the time derivative of the aforementioned function stays below the needed threshold.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The token bucket algorithm is directly comparable to one of the two versions of the leaky bucket algorithm described in the literature.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] This comparable version of the leaky bucket is described on the relevant Wikipedia page as the leaky bucket algorithm as a meter.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] There is, however, another version of the leaky bucket algorithm, described on the relevant Wikipedia page as the leaky bucket algorithm as a queue.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] This is a special case of the leaky bucket as a meter, which can be described by the conforming packets passing through the bucket.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The leaky bucket as a queue is therefore applicable only to traffic shaping, and does not, in general, allow the output packet stream to be bursty, i.e., it is jitter free.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] It is therefore significantly different from the token bucket algorithm.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] These two versions of the leaky bucket algorithm have both been described in the literature under the same name.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] This has led to considerable confusion over the properties of that algorithm and its comparison with the token bucket algorithm.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] However, fundamentally, the two algorithms are the same, and will, if implemented correctly and given the same parameters, see exactly the same packets as conforming and nonconforming.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The hierarchical token bucket (HTB) is a faster replacement for the class-based queueing (CBQ) queuing discipline in Linux.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] It is useful for limiting each client's download/upload rate so that the limited client cannot saturate the total bandwidth.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Conceptually, HTB is an arbitrary number of token buckets arranged in a hierarchy.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] The primary egress queuing discipline (*qdisc*) on any device is known as the root qdisc.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] This single HTB class will be set with two parameters, a *rate* and a *ceil*.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] These values should be the same for the top-level class and will represent the total available bandwidth on the link.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] In HTB, *rate* means the guaranteed bandwidth available for a given class and *ceil* (short for ceiling) indicates the maximum bandwidth that class is allowed to consume.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] When a class requests a bandwidth more than guaranteed, it may borrow bandwidth from its parent as long as both ceils are not reached.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] When choosing the bandwidth for a top-level class, traffic shaping only helps at the bottleneck between the LAN and the Internet.
[src:traffic-shaping/token-bucket] Typically, this is the case in home and office network environments, where an entire LAN is serviced by a DSL or T1 connection.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] In communications, **traffic policing** is the process of monitoring network traffic for compliance with a traffic contract and taking steps to enforce that contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic sources which are aware of a traffic contract may apply traffic shaping to ensure their output stays within the contract and is thus not discarded.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic exceeding a traffic contract may be discarded immediately, marked as non-compliant, or left as-is, depending on administrative policy and the characteristics of the excess traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The recipient of traffic that has been *policed* will observe packet loss distributed throughout periods when incoming traffic exceeded the contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] If the source does not limit its sending rate (for example, through a feedback mechanism), this will continue, and may appear to the recipient as if link errors or some other disruption is causing random packet loss.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The received traffic, which has experienced policing en route, will typically comply with the contract, although jitter may be introduced by elements in the network downstream of the policer.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] With reliable protocols, such as TCP as opposed to UDP, the dropped packets will not be acknowledged by the receiver, and therefore will be resent by the emitter, thus generating more traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Sources with feedback-based congestion control mechanisms (for example TCP) typically adapt rapidly to static policing, converging on a rate just below the policed sustained rate.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Co-operative policing mechanisms, such as packet-based discard facilitate more rapid convergence, higher stability and more efficient resource sharing.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] As a result, it may be hard for endpoints to distinguish TCP traffic that has been merely policed from TCP traffic that has been shaped.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Where cell-level dropping is enforced (as opposed to that achieved through packet-based policing) the impact is particularly severe on longer packets.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Since cells are typically much shorter than the maximum packet size, conventional policers discard cells which do not respect packet boundaries, and hence the total amount of traffic dropped will typically be distributed throughout a number of packets.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Almost all known packet reassembly mechanisms will respond to a missing cell by dropping the packet entirely, and consequently a very large number of packet losses can result from moderately exceeding the policed contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2475 describes traffic policing elements like a *meter* and a *dropper*.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] They may also optionally include a *marker*.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The meter measures the traffic and determines whether or not it exceeds the contract (for example by GCRA).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Where it exceeds the contract, some policy determines if any given PDU is dropped, or if marking is implemented, if and how it is to be marked.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Marking can comprise setting a congestion flag (such as ECN flag of TCP or CLP bit of ATM) or setting a traffic aggregate indication (such as Differentiated Services Code Point of IP).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] In simple implementations, traffic is classified into two categories, or "colors" : compliant (green) and in excess (red).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2697 proposes a more precise classification, with three "colors".
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] In this document, the contract is described through three parameters: **Committed Information Rate** (CIR), **Committed Burst Size** (CBS), and **Excess Burst Size** (EBS).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] A packet is "green" if it doesn't exceed the CBS, "yellow" if it does exceed the CBS, but not the EBS, and "red" otherwise.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The "single-rate three-color marker" described by RFC 2697 allows for temporary bursts.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The bursts are allowed when the line was under-used before they appeared.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] A more predictable algorithm is described in RFC 2698, which proposes a "double-rate three-color marker".
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2698 defines a new parameter, the Peak Information Rate (PIR).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2859 describes the "Time Sliding Window Three Colour Marker" which meters a traffic stream and marks packets based on measured throughput relative to two specified rates: Committed Target Rate (CTR) and Peak Target Rate (PTR).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] On Cisco equipment, both traffic policing and shaping are implemented through the token bucket algorithm.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic policing in ATM networks is known as Usage/Network Parameter Control.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The network can also discard non-conformant traffic in the network (using Priority Control).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] The reference for both traffic policing and traffic shaping in ATM (given by the ATM Forum and the ITU-T) is the Generic Cell Rate Algorithm (GCRA), which is described as a version of the leaky bucket algorithm.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] However, comparison of the leaky bucket and token bucket algorithms shows that they are simply mirror images of one another, one adding bucket content where the other takes it away and taking away bucket content where the other adds it.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Hence, given equivalent parameters, implementations of both algorithms will see exactly the same traffic as conforming and non-conforming.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic policing requires maintenance of numerical statistics and measures for each policed traffic flow, but it does not require implementation or management of significant volumes of packet buffer.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Consequently, it is significantly less complex to implement than *traffic shaping*.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Connection-oriented networks (for example ATM systems) can perform Connection Admission Control (CAC) based on traffic contracts.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] In the context of Voice over IP (VoIP), this is also known as Call Admission Control (CAC).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] An application that wishes to use a connection-oriented network to transport traffic must first request a connection (through signalling, for example Q.2931), which involves informing the network about the characteristics of the traffic and the quality of service (QoS) required by the application.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] This information is matched against a traffic contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] If the connection request is accepted, the application is permitted to use the network to transport traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] This function protects the network resources from malicious connections and enforces the compliance of every connection to its negotiated traffic contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-policing-communications] Difference between CAC and traffic policing is that CAC is an *a priori* verification (before the transfer occurs), while traffic policing is an *a posteriori* verification (during the transfer).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] One type of traffic shaping is application-based traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] In application-based traffic shaping, fingerprinting tools are first used to identify applications of interest, which are then subject to shaping policies.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Some controversial cases of application-based traffic shaping include bandwidth throttling of peer-to-peer file sharing traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Many application protocols use encryption to circumvent application-based traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Another type of traffic shaping is route-based traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Route-based traffic shaping is conducted based on previous-hop or next-hop information.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] If a link becomes utilized to the point where there is a significant level of congestion, latency can rise substantially.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping can be used to prevent this from occurring and keep latency in check.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping provides a means to control the volume of traffic being sent into a network in a specified period (bandwidth throttling), or the maximum rate at which the traffic is sent (rate limiting), or more complex criteria such as generic cell rate algorithm.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] This control can be accomplished in many ways and for many reasons; however, traffic shaping is always achieved by delaying packets.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping is commonly applied at the network edges to control traffic entering the network, but can also be applied by the traffic source (for example, computer or network card) or by an element in the network.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping is sometimes applied by traffic sources to ensure the traffic they send complies with a contract, which may be enforced in the network by traffic policing.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Shaping is widely used for teletraffic engineering, and appears in domestic ISPs' networks as one of several Internet Traffic Management Practices (ITMPs).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Some Internet service providers (ISPs) may use traffic shaping to limit resources consumed by peer-to-peer file-sharing networks, such as BitTorrent.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Data centers use traffic shaping to maintain service level agreements for the variety of applications and the many tenants hosted as they all share the same physical network.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Audio Video Bridging includes an integral traffic-shaping provision defined in IEEE 802.1Qav.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Nodes in an IP network that buffer packets before sending on a link that is at capacity produce an unintended traffic shaping effect.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] This can appear across, for example, a low bandwidth link, a particularly expensive WAN link or satellite hop.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] A traffic shaper works by delaying metered traffic such that each packet complies with the relevant traffic contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Metering may be implemented with, for example, the leaky bucket or token bucket algorithms (the former typically in ATM and the latter in IP networks).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Metered packets or cells are then stored in a FIFO buffer, one for each separately shaped class, until they can be transmitted in compliance with the associated traffic contract.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Transmission may occur immediately (if the traffic arriving at the shaper is already compliant), after some delay (waiting in the buffer until its scheduled release time) or never (in case of packet loss).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] All traffic shaper implementations have a finite buffer and must cope with the case where the buffer is full.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] A simple and common approach is to drop traffic arriving while the buffer is full a strategy known as tail drop and which results in traffic policing as well as shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] A more sophisticated implementation could apply a dropping algorithm such as random early detection.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Simple traffic shaping schemes shape all traffic uniformly.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] More sophisticated shapers first classify traffic.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] *Traffic classification* categorises traffic (for example, based on port number or protocol).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Different *classes* can then be shaped separately to achieve a desired effect.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] A *self-limiting source* produces traffic which never exceeds some upper bound, for example, media sources which cannot transmit faster than their encoded rate allows.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Self-limiting sources shape the traffic they generate to a greater or lesser degree.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Congestion control mechanisms can also affect traffic shaping of sorts - for example, TCP's window mechanism implements a variable rate constraint related to bandwidth-delay product.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] TCP Nice, a modified version of TCP developed by researchers at the University of Texas at Austin, allows applications to request that certain TCP connections be managed by the operating system as near-zero-cost background transfers, or *nice* flows.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Such flows interfere only minimally with foreground (non-nice) flows, while reaping a large fraction of spare network bandwidth.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping is a specific technique and one of several that, combined, constitute bandwidth management.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping is of interest, especially to ISPs.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Their high-cost, high-traffic networks are their major assets, and as such, are the focus of their attention.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] They sometimes use traffic shaping to optimize the use of their network, sometimes by shaping traffic according to their assessment of importance and thus discouraging use of certain applications.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Most companies with remote offices are now connected via a wide area network (WAN).
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Applications tend to be centrally hosted at the head office and remote offices are expected to pull data from central databases and server farms.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping is thus a good means for companies to avoid purchasing additional bandwidth while properly managing these resources.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Alternatives to traffic shaping in this regard are application acceleration and WAN optimization and compression, which are fundamentally different from traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Traffic shaping defines bandwidth rules, whereas application acceleration uses multiple techniques like a TCP performance-enhancing proxy.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] WAN optimization, on the other hand, compresses data streams or sends only differences in file updates.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] The latter is quite effective for chatty protocols like CIFS.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] There are several methods to detect and measure traffic shaping.
[src:traffic-shaping/traffic-shaping] Tools have been developed to assist with detection.
